                            MBBSHTML Documentation

     .-------------------.
     | WHAT IS MBBSHTML? |-------------------------------------------------
     `-------------------'

      MBBSHTML is a utility used to create HTML web pages based on your
      Mystic BBS file area listings.  100% of the created web page is
      configurable by templates.  This program is used to maintain the
      file pages on the official Mystic BBS web page!

     .-------------------------------.
     | MBBSHTML COMMAND LINE OPTIONS |-------------------------------------
     `-------------------------------'

      There are several command line options needed in orded to use this
      utility.  Below is a basic description.  A more detailed explaination
      will be available in the templates section of the documentation.

      MBBSHTML [mystic_dir] [template_1] [template_2] [template_3] [output]

      [mystic_dir]  The root path of your Mystic BBS installation.  In
                    other words, MBBSHTML will look for MYSTIC.DAT in this
                    directory.

      [template_1]  The template used for the web page that will be
                    created.

      [template_2]  The template used for each file listed on the web
                    page.

      [template_3]  An optional template.  When used, it will alternate
                    with template_2.  In other words, the first file in the
                    listing will use [template_2], the next file will
                    use [template_3], the third file will use [template_2]
                    and so on.  If you do not wish to use this template,
                    just supply "NONE" (without the quotes) on the command
                    line for the [template_3] name.

      [output]      This is the file name of the output file, ie, the
                    finalize file listing created by MBBSHTML.

     .-------------------------------------.
     | CREATING YOUR [TEMPLATE_1] TEMPLATE |-------------------------------
     `-------------------------------------'

      [TEMPLATE_1] is the backbone of the created .HTML file listing.  All
      HTML code for the produced page should be listed here, except for the
      actual file listing code which is produced by MBBSHTML and
      [TEMPLATE_2] and [TEMPLATE_3].  Inside of this template you must list
      which file bases should be included.  This is done by using a simple
      command embedded in the template:

         <!--MBBSHTML:<file_area_data>,<file_area_path>-->

         The <file_area_data> field should contain the storage file name
         for the file area, as setup in MCFG's file base editor.  If you
         have a filename of UPLOADS set for your Uploads base inside of
         MCFG, then you'd use UPLOADS here to tell MBBSHTML that you
         want to list all files in that base.

         <file_area_path> is the path that will be returned by the @PATH@
         MCI code used in the [TEMPLATE_2] and [TEMPLATE_3] files.

     An unlimited number of file bases can be defined in a single template
     file.  An example of a simple [TEMPLATE_1] file might be:

      <html>
        <head>
          <title>MBBSHTML file listing</title>
        </head>

        <body>
          <h3>Recent Uploads:</h3>
          <!--MBBSHTML:UPLOADS,uploads/-->
          <p>
          <h3>General Files</h3>
          <!--MBBSHTML:GENERAL,general/-->
        </body>
      </html>

     .-------------------------------------.
     | CREATING YOUR [TEMPLATE_2] TEMPLATE |-------------------------------
     `-------------------------------------'

      [TEMPLATE_2] defines the HTML code to use for each file listed in
      the produced web page.  The following MCI codes are supported for
      this file, and will be replaced by their corresponding data:

         @LNAME@ : The file name converted to all lower cased letters
         @UNAME@ : The file name converted to all upper cased letters
         @SIZEK@ : The file size in kilo-bytes
         @SIZEB@ : The file size in bytes
         @DESC@  : The file description
         @PATH@  : The file path as defined within [TEMPLATE_1]

      An example of a simple [TEMPLATE_2] file might be:

      <b>@UNAME@</b> @SIZEK@ KB @DESC@
      <p>

     .-------------------------------------.
     | CREATING YOUR [TEMPLATE_3] TEMPLATE |-------------------------------
     `-------------------------------------'

      [TEMPLATE_3] is identical in all ways to the [TEMPLATE_2] file.  When
      used, it will be alternated with the [TEMPLATE_2] file for every
      other file entry.  For example:

         First file  = [TEMPLATE_2]
         Second file = [TEMPLATE_3]
         Third file  = [TEMPLATE_2]
         Fourth file = [TEMPLATE_3]
         ... (and so on)

      This is useful for creating a file listing inside of a table with
      every other file having a different color background.
                    
     .----------------------------.
     | EXAMPLES OF USING MBBSHTML |----------------------------------------
     `----------------------------'

      MBBSHTML comes with a default set of templates.  If you don't quite
      understand on the concept of how MBBSHTML works yet, you may wish to
      experiment with these included templates.

      The first thing you need to do is open up MCFG and select a file
      base that you know has files in it.  Edit the base settings and
      observe the "FILE NAME:" setting.  In our example, the file base
      we're using has a file name setting of "UPLOADS".

      Next you should open up the TEMPLATE_1 file, which is found as
      temp_upload.html.  Find the line which has this text on it:

      <!--MBBSHTML:FILENAME,files/-->

      Now change FILENAME to whatever the file name field was for the
      area you picked out in MCFG.  In our example, we used UPLOADS:

      <!--MBBSHTML:UPLOADS,uploads/-->

      The second field is the path to the files.  We'll change that to
      uploads/ for our example.  This field doesn't effect MBBSHTML, it
      is just used for the @PATH@ MCI code in the [TEMPLATE_2] file.

      Now save template_uploads.html and we're ready to produce a file
      listing HTML!  Now we execute MBBSHTML:

      MBBSHTML C:\MYSTIC temp_uploads.html temp_file1.html NONE output.html

      Make sure you replace C:\MYSTIC with whatever path your Mystic
      installation resides in.  If all goes well, you should be able to
      open up output.html with your web browser and see the file listing
      produced by MBBSHTML.

      If the above output.html was successful, try replacing the NONE
      command line option with temp_file2.html.  This is the alternate
      file listing template (TEMPLATE_3).  Afterwards, open up your
      browser and see how this template was used to make each file entry
      have a different background color.

